history.content:
you should know how trees and hashing work, and the runtime complexity of various algorithms, all of which are heavily covered in 61b. 

There was also a tiny bit on dynamic programming, but it was just one small thing. Also a little on graphs, but nothing terribly complex. Runtime + hashing was probably the most important, plus having lots of Java experience.

 

-

Adding on (I'm not the same person as ^^^): I just took 186 this past Spring, and I would strongly advise you don't take it without having gone through 61B. The projects alone pretty much require knowledge of most of the data structures of 61B, in addition to knowing how to use IntelliJ (you will NOT be able to successfully do these projects in Sublime), debugging tools, etc. 

-

I agree with what has been written above. That said, it ultimately depends on your level of prior/outside experience. Take a look at the slides and Project 1 spec from last semester and decide for yourself. (Project 1 was released ~3 weeks in.)
